Pretoria - Ensuring early childhood education is up to standard was the focus of the day as the first ladies of South Africa and China visited learners in Mamelodi West this morning. Dr Tshepo Motsepe and Mrs Peng Liyuan visited the Uthando Daycare Centre in Sunvalley as part of the 10th annual BRICS summit Spousal Programme. Motsepe said she was happy that the first lady of China had come to the community to highlight the importance of early childhood development. Peng cheerfully told the learners: "You are all welcome to visit China." The learners then demonstrated to the first ladies what they had learned about safety and reporting sexual abuse of any kind through singing. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. This year's summit is an auspicious event as the country is celebrating the centenary of former president Nelson Mandela's birthday. The summit is being attended by the heads of state and government of five member states. Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa, will be convening under the theme: "BRICS in Africa: Collaboration for Inclusive Growth and shared prosperity in the fourth Industrial revolution." Pretoria News